               <note>
                  <ab type="history">Waǧ is a historical region in <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa"/> 
                south of the river <placeName ref="LOC4892Mugar"/>
                     which flows into the <placeName ref="LOC1022Abbay"/> west of <placeName ref="INS0341DL"/> 
                of <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa"/>.
                     It was one of the seven districts of <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa"/> 
                which contributed to troops to <persName ref="PRS10303Yekunno"/>
                     for his campaign against the last Zāgʷe king. It was also the native region
                     of <persName ref="PRS6734MarhaKr"/> the 15th century 9th 
                  <roleName type="title">ʾǝč̣č̣age</roleName> of 
                <placeName ref="INS0341DL"/>. The history of 
                Waǧ is closely connected to  its neighbour on the east 
                <placeName ref="LOC3061Fataga"/>. <persName ref="PRS1854Amdase"/> 
                is reported to have defeated the Zebdār of Waǧ  
                  and appointed a governor with the title Masfǝn. During the time
                  of <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS10626ZaraY"/> the governor bore the title hǝgāno,
                a possible indication that the district was Islamic by that time. During the time 
                of <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>  
                     <persName ref="PRS2334BaedaM"/> it served as an
                important strategic region to conduct military campaigns against
                <placeName ref="LOC1095Adal"/>. 
                  Following the death of <persName ref="PRS1522Ahmadb"/>, 
                Waǧ was also a stronghold of King <persName ref="PRS4428Galawdew"/> where he built his royal seat 
                  in<date>1550</date>. In <date>1577</date>, <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName> 
                     <persName ref="PRS8550sardaDe"/>, on his way to attack 
                     sultān of <placeName ref="LOC1095Adal"/>, passed through Waǧ.</ab>
               </note>               
